Level 1: Does the clinical documentation describe the patient's primary cancer condition?, answer YES or NO
Level 2: Is ther any Cancer Stage information in the notes?, answer YES or NO
Level 3: Identify the cancer staging classification system that was used other than TNM or lymphoma staging. Look for an explicit reference to a staging system such as FIGO (gynecologic), Binet or Rai (leukemia), Breslow Depth or Clark Level (melanoma), ISS or RISS (myeloma), INSS or INRGSS (neuroblastoma), Gleason Grade (prostate), Rhabdomyosarcoma Clinical Group, or Wilms Tumor staging.

Only populate if the cancer is lymphoma. What is the staging of lymphoma (both Hodgkins and Non-Hodgkins) by Ann Arbor, Cotswold, or Lugano staging systems? Also report the specific staging system used.
What is the T-category of the TNM staging system?
What is the N-category of the TNM staging system?
What is the M-category of the TNM staging system?
If the Staging Method is detected/populated with a staging system that is not TNM or one of the lymphoma systems, populate this field with the stage type in that system.

Level 1: Records the history of secondary neoplasms, including location(s) and the date of onset of metastases. A secondary cancer results from the spread (metastasization) of cancer from its original site.
Are there results or mentions of any tumor marker tests in the clinical notes?, answer YES or NO
Level 2: The name of the clinical test or procedure performed on a patient. A tumor marker is a substance found in tissue or blood or other body fluids that may be a sign of cancer or certain benign (non-cancer) conditions. Most tumor markers are made by both normal cells and cancer cells, but they are made in larger amounts by cancer cells. A tumor marker may help to diagnose cancer, plan treatment, or find out how well treatment is working or if cancer has come back. Examples of tumor markers include CA-125 (in ovarian cancer), CA 15-3 (in breast cancer), CEA (in colon cancer), and PSA (in prostate cancer). Tumor markers differ from genomic markers in that they are measured at the levels of the protein and substance post-RNA protein synthesis.
